# Local auto-push (current branch)

When enabled, this rule makes the agent commit and push at the end of any complete reply that actually modified project files. It is **opt-in per repo** and runs only in `MODE: Local`.

## Trigger gate (check first, in this order)

This rule is **active** only when **all** of the following are true:

1. `MODE: Local` (per `00-universal-core.mdc`).
2. The marker file `.cursor/.local-auto-push` exists at the repo root.
3. This reply (the parent reply, including any sub-agent replies that returned to you) **modified at least one project file**, where "project file" means any path **outside** the following exclusion list:
   - `.cursor/agent-transcripts/**`
   - `terminals/**`
   - `.cursor/.local-auto-push` (the marker itself)
   - Any path matched by `.gitignore`

   If only excluded paths changed, write `Auto-push: N/A (no project-file modifications this reply)` in the Done check and skip the rest of this rule.

If any of (1)–(3) fail: write the failing condition in the Done check and skip.

## Preconditions (any failure → stop and report; do **not** push)

Before staging, verify:

1. **Not on a detached HEAD.** `git symbolic-ref --quiet HEAD` must succeed. If detached, stop and tell the user — do not commit a dangling SHA.
2. **Pre-push hygiene done** per `docs-sync-before-finish.mdc`: docs synced, `.gitignore` reviewed, secret-leak scan **clean**.
3. **`CHANGELOG.md` entry written and version bumped** per `versioning-and-changelog.mdc`.
4. **No merge / rebase / cherry-pick / bisect in progress.** Check for `.git/MERGE_HEAD`, `.git/REBASE_HEAD`, `.git/CHERRY_PICK_HEAD`, `.git/BISECT_LOG`.
5. **Fast-forward is possible.** Run `git fetch origin "$(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD)" || true`, then `git rev-list --left-right --count HEAD...@{u}` (if upstream exists). If remote has commits we don't have:
   - Try `git pull --rebase origin "$(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD)"`.
   - If the rebase has any conflict — even one file — abort with `git rebase --abort` and stop. Do not auto-resolve.

## Push procedure — MUST

1. Stage **everything**:

   ```bash
   git add -A
   ```

2. Commit using the Conventional Commits convention required by `versioning-and-changelog.mdc`:

   ```bash
   git commit -m "<type>(<scope>): <subject>" -m "<body explaining what + why>"
   ```

3. Push the **current branch** to its corresponding remote branch:
   - First push of a new branch (no upstream set):

     ```bash
     git push -u origin HEAD
     ```

   - Subsequent pushes:

     ```bash
     git push origin HEAD
     ```

4. After push completes, `post-push-ci-green.mdc` fires automatically. You **must** watch CI to green (or to a documented stop condition). There is no Local opt-out.

## You MUST NOT

- `git push --force` or `git push --force-with-lease`. Never. If the push is rejected, stop and tell the user.
- Push to any branch other than the current branch. (You wanted current-branch behavior, not "always push to main".)
- `git add` a file that triggered the secret-leak scan in `docs-sync-before-finish.mdc`. The scan is a hard stop.
- Bypass the version bump — every push gets a new `CHANGELOG.md` entry.
- Push when on a detached HEAD, in the middle of a merge/rebase, or after a non-fast-forward fetch you couldn't resolve cleanly.
- Push from a Scenario-B sub-agent (shared workspace). See `00-universal-core.mdc` "Sub-agent commit/push policy".

## Required report (in your final message)

- `Auto-push: <pushed | N/A: <reason> | blocked: <reason>>`
- If pushed: branch name, commit SHA, version bumped from `X.Y.Z` to `X.Y.Z'`.
- If blocked: name the failing precondition.

## How to enable in a repo

```bash
mkdir -p .cursor && touch .cursor/.local-auto-push
git add .cursor/.local-auto-push
git commit -m "chore(cursor): enable local auto-push for current branch"
```

The marker file itself is tracked (so all developers on the repo share the policy). To temporarily disable on one machine, rename it locally — but be aware your teammates still have auto-push on.
